# Full-Stack Deployment Guide

I've successfully prepared your codebase for cloud deployment. Here is your step-by-step guide to taking your application live.

## 1. Push to GitHub

I have already initialized Git on your local machine and committed your files. Now you just need to create the remote repository and push it.

> [!NOTE]  
> If you don't have a GitHub account, create one at [github.com](https://github.com/).

1. Go to [GitHub - Create a New Repository](https://github.com/new).
2. Name your repository something like `loan-management-app`.
3. Leave it as "Public" or "Private" and click **Create repository**.
4. In the page that appears, look for the section titled **"…or push an existing repository from the command line"**.
5. Copy the 3 lines of code provided there.
6. Open your terminal in the root of your project (`C:\Users\jayap\loan app`) and paste those commands. It will look like this:
   ```bash
   git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/loan-management-app.git
   git branch -M main
   git push -u origin main
   ```

## 2. Set up the Database (Neon.tech)

Vercel doesn't run a local PostgreSQL database, so you need a free cloud database.

1. Go to [Neon.tech](https://neon.tech/) and sign up for a free account.
2. Create a new project (name it `loan-app-db`).
3. Once the database is created, you will see a **Connection String** on your dashboard (it starts with `postgresql://`).
4. Copy this string. You will need it in the next step.

## 3. Deploy the Backend (Render)

We will use Render to host your Node.js backend.

1. Go to [Render.com](https://render.com/) and sign up using your GitHub account.
2. Click **New +** and select **Web Service**.
3. Choose **Build and deploy from a Git repository** and connect your GitHub account.
4. Select the `loan-management-app` repository you just created.
5. In the service settings:
   - Name: `loan-app-backend`
   - **Root Directory**: Type `loan-app-backend` (this is crucial so Render knows where the backend code is).
   - Build Command: `npm install`
   - Start Command: `node src/app.js`
6. Scroll down to **Environment Variables** and add two variables:
   - `DATABASE_URL`: *(paste the connection string you copied from Neon.tech)*
   - `PORT`: `3000` (Render might auto-assign a port, that's completely fine, our app handles it).
7. Select the **Free plan** and click **Create Web Service**.
8. Wait for it to build and deploy. Once finished, copy the **Render URL** (e.g., `https://loan-app-backend-xyz.onrender.com`). You will need this for Vercel.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Because you are using a new database, your user accounts won't be copied over. You will need to click the "Register" button to create a new user account on the live database. Wait for the backend to finish deploying before doing this!

## 4. Deploy the Frontend (Vercel)

Now we deploy the frontend and point it to the backend.

1. Go to [Vercel.com](https://vercel.com/) and sign in with GitHub.
2. Click **Add New Project**.
3. Select the `loan-management-app` repository you created.
4. In the configuration settings:
   - **Framework Preset**: Vercel should automatically detect **Vite**.
   - **Root Directory**: Click "Edit" and select `client` (this tells Vercel where the React code is).
5. Open the **Environment Variables** section and add:
   - Name: `VITE_API_URL`
   - Value: *(paste the Render URL you copied in step 3)*
6. Click **Deploy**.

**Congratulations!** 🚀 Once Vercel finishes deploying, they will give you a live URL for your frontend. You can share this link with anyone, and it will be communicating with your cloud backend and cloud database!
